# Shared chrome — no divergence between Atlas ecosystem apps

File Atlas (`apps/file-atlas`) and Slate (`apps/slate`) must remain visually
and behaviorally identical at the chrome level (unified top bar, left tools
rail, bottom readouts, advanced window, theme).

Hard rules:

1. All chrome painting, colors, spacing, and layout primitives live in
   `crates/atlas-shell` (`theme.rs`, `menubar.rs`, `tabs.rs`, `sidebar.rs`,
   `dock.rs`, `taper.rs`, `widgets.rs`, `chrome.rs`, `commands.rs`, and
   `ui-tokens.toml`). Apps pass data in and handle returned actions. **Read
   `crates/atlas-shell/TOPBAR.md` before changing the top bar** — one unified
   strip (icon portal + inline tabs + window controls); never split title bar
   and tab strip into separate rows again. Adjustable top-bar values belong in
   `ui-tokens.toml`, not scattered constants. Follow
   `docs/ui-tuning-workflow.md` when adding tunable UI areas. Read
   `crates/atlas-shell/DOCK.md` before changing floating canvas docks, and
   `crates/atlas-shell/PAINT.md` before adding soft AA strokes (partition
   ribbons, etc.).
2. Never hardcode chrome colors or repaint tab/sidebar shapes inside an app
   crate. If a new chrome capability is needed, extend `atlas-shell` so both
   apps inherit it.
3. `egui`/`eframe` and other shared dependency versions are pinned once in the
   workspace `Cargo.toml` under `[workspace.dependencies]`; member crates must
   reference them with `{ workspace = true }`.
4. Every user-facing keyboard/mouse binding must be registered in the app's
   `commands.rs` `ENTRIES` table (see each app's `COMMANDS.md`) so the
   Advanced window reference stays complete.
5. Tagging is a Slate-only concept: File Atlas must not grow its own tag
   model. Atlas surfaces Slate workbook tags exclusively through
   `crates/atlas-session` during linked sessions.
6. The AI panel body is shared: both apps render it via
   `atlas_ai::ui::ai_body`. AI/Cursor behavior (workspace config, launcher,
   context beacon) lives in `crates/atlas-ai`, never per-app.
